================================================================================
EXCEL POWER QUERY BLUEPRINT: SMART SERVICENOW TICKET TRACKER (DATABASE STYLE)
================================================================================
This blueprint guides you through setting up a self-referencing "UPSERT" 
tracking system in Excel using Power Query. 

Key Capabilities:
1. Automatically updates changed statuses for existing PRBs.
2. Automatically appends new PRBs from fresh exports.
3. Preserves historic PRBs even after they drop off the ServiceNow export.
4. Securely locks manual notes (Category, Issue, Workaround, Version Fix) to 
   the unique PRB Number so they never shift or misalign.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 1: PREPARE YOUR EXCEL SHEETS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Create two distinct worksheets in a single Excel workbook:

1. Worksheet Name: ServiceNow_Drop
   - Paste your current raw ServiceNow export here.
   - Headers MUST include: PRB Number, PRB Created, PRB Updated, Short description, 
     Problem Owner, Assigned to, Assignment group, State, Closed.
   - Select all the data (including headers) and press CTRL + T.
   - Go to the 'Table Design' tab on the top ribbon.
   - On the far left, rename the table to: ServiceNow_Raw

2. Worksheet Name: Master_Tracker
   - This is your initial tracking sheet. It must contain the same ServiceNow 
     headers, plus your 4 custom manual columns: Category, Issue, Workaround, 
     Version Fix.
   - Select all data (including headers) and press CTRL + T.
   - Go to the 'Table Design' tab on the top ribbon.
   - On the far left, rename the table to: Master_Table

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 2: LOAD TABLES INTO POWER QUERY AS CONNECTIONS ONLY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Introduce both tables to Power Query without generating duplicate sheets yet.

1. Load ServiceNow Data:
   - Click any cell inside the 'ServiceNow_Raw' table.
   - Go to the 'Data' tab on the top Excel ribbon.
   - Click 'From Table/Range' (or 'From Sheet'). The Power Query Editor will open.
   - Do not make any edits yet. In the top-left corner, click the arrow next to 
     'Close & Load' and select 'Close & Load To...'.
   - In the popup dialog, select 'Only Create Connection' and click OK.

2. Load Master Data:
   - Click any cell inside the 'Master_Table' table.
   - Go to the 'Data' tab on the top Excel ribbon.
   - Click 'From Table/Range'.
   - In the top-left corner, click the arrow next to 'Close & Load' and select 
     'Close & Load To...'.
   - Select 'Only Create Connection' and click OK.

* Verification: You will now see both 'ServiceNow_Raw' and 'Master_Table' listed 
  in the 'Queries & Connections' side pane on the right of your Excel screen.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 3: CREATE QUERY #1 - ISOLATE THE "VANISHED" PRBS (SAFETY NET)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This query identifies historical PRBs that are no longer part of your live 
ServiceNow export files, preventing data loss.

1. In the right-side 'Queries & Connections' pane, RIGHT-CLICK 'Master_Table' 
   and select 'Reference'. The Power Query Editor will open.
2. In the left-side Queries pane, double-click this new query and rename it to:
   Vanished_PRBs
3. In the 'Home' tab at the top ribbon, click 'Merge Queries'.
4. In the middle dropdown menu of the Merge window, select: ServiceNow_Raw
5. Map the unique keys: Click the 'PRB Number' column header in the top preview, 
   then click the 'PRB Number' column header in the bottom preview. A green 
   checkmark will appear indicating a successful match.
6. Look for 'Join Kind' at the bottom of the window. Change it to:
   Left Anti (rows only in first)
7. Click OK.
8. Scroll to the far right of the table preview. You will see a column named 
   'ServiceNow_Raw' filled with 'Table' values. RIGHT-CLICK that column header 
   and select 'Remove'. (We only used it as a filter; the data itself isn't needed).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 4: CREATE QUERY #2 - THE MAIN UPDATER (FINAL_TRACKER)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This query pulls the fresh ServiceNow data and aligns your historical manual 
notes safely alongside it, performing automatic status updates.

1. In the left-side Queries pane of the Power Query Editor, RIGHT-CLICK your 
   original 'ServiceNow_Raw' query and select 'Reference'.
2. Double-click this new query at the bottom of the list and rename it to:
   Final_Tracker
3. In the 'Home' tab at the top ribbon, click 'Merge Queries'.
4. In the middle dropdown menu of the Merge window, select: Master_Table
5. Map the unique keys: Click the 'PRB Number' column header in both the top 
   and bottom preview boxes.
6. Ensure the 'Join Kind' is set to: 
   Left Outer (all from first, matching from second)
7. Click OK.
8. Scroll to the far right to find the new 'Master_Table' column. Click the 
   'Expand' icon (two small opposing arrows) in the column header.
9. UNCHECK the box for "Use original column name as prefix".
10. UNCHECK all columns EXCEPT your 4 manual annotation columns: 
    Check ONLY 'Category', 'Issue', 'Workaround', and 'Version Fix'. 
11. Click OK.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 5: COMBINE THE DATA (THE APPEND STEP)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bring back your historical "vanished" items to create a unified database.

1. While still working inside the 'Final_Tracker' query, go to the 'Home' tab 
   and click 'Append Queries'.
2. In the popup window, leave it selected as 'Two tables'.
3. In the dropdown menu for the table to append, select: Vanished_PRBs
4. Click OK.
5. (Optional but Recommended): Click the drop-down arrow on the 'PRB Number' 
   column header and select 'Sort Ascending' so your table stays organized numerically.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 6: OUTPUT AND LOCK THE LOOP (DO THIS ONLY ONCE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Establish the closed loop environment so Power Query reads and writes from the 
exact same sheet.

1. In the top-left corner of the Power Query window, click the main 
   'Close & Load' button.
2. Power Query will close and compile. A brand new worksheet tab will be generated 
   containing your final database table.
3. Clean up the workbook to avoid confusion:
   - Locate your original 'Master_Tracker' worksheet (the one you had before starting).
   - RIGHT-CLICK that worksheet tab and choose DELETE.
4. Go to the NEW worksheet tab just generated by Power Query:
   - Rename the worksheet tab to: Master_Tracker
   - Click any cell inside the newly generated table.
   - Go to the 'Table Design' tab on the top ribbon.
   - On the far left, rename this table to exactly: Master_Table

The database loop is now complete and active.

================================================================================
HOW TO USE AND MAINTAIN YOUR SMART SYSTEM MOVING FORWARD
================================================================================

1. UPDATING WITH NEW SERVICENOW DATA (Weekly/Monthly):
   - Open your fresh export from ServiceNow. Copy only the data rows (do not 
     copy headers).
   - Go to your 'ServiceNow_Drop' sheet. Select all old data rows below the 
     headers and press 'Delete'.
   - Paste your new data into the first empty row below the headers. The 
     Excel table will auto-expand.
   - Navigate to your 'Master_Tracker' sheet, RIGHT-CLICK anywhere inside the 
     table, and click 'Refresh'.
   - Statuses will update, new PRBs appear, vanished items remain, and your 
     notes stay perfectly preserved.

2. ADDING/EDITING MANUAL NOTES:
   - Type your notes ('Category', 'Issue', 'Workaround', 'Version Fix') directly 
     inside the 'Master_Tracker' sheet. 
   - Power Query reads what you type here, caches it safely during a refresh, 
     and writes it back. Never type notes on the raw drop sheet.

3. PERMANENTLY DELETING OLD DATA (Housecleaning):
   - Because the system acts as an absolute archive, deleting a PRB from the 
     raw drop sheet will not remove it from your tracker (it will just be marked 
     as vanished and kept alive).
   - To completely destroy an old row (e.g., tickets older than 1 year):
     A. Ensure the item is no longer in your active ServiceNow raw export.
     B. Go to the 'Master_Tracker' table, RIGHT-CLICK the specific row you 
        want gone, and select Delete > Table Rows.
     C. Click 'Refresh'. The row is now permanently purged from the system.
